    <h1>Christopher Watson</h1>

    <p>My name is Chris Watson and I'm a fourth year Ph.D. student at the University of Pennsylvania,
      where I am very fortunate to be advised by <a href="https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~alur/">Rajeev Alur</a> and <a href="https://www.seas.upenn.edu/~dineshj/">Dinesh Jayaraman</a>. I am very interested in
      (and currently working on!) integrating logical specifications, machine perception, and reinforcement learning to synthesize control policies for
      long horizon tasks.</p>

    <p>I am a proud member of Penn's
      <a href="https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~plclub/">PLClub</a> and the <a href="https://asset.seas.upenn.edu/">ASSET center</a>
      (where I was recently featured in an <a href="https://asset.seas.upenn.edu/penns-asset-center/">article</a> that describes our goal of safe,
      explainable, and trustworthy AI!). During Summer 2024, I interned at the NASA Ames research center, where I started collaborating with <a href="https://www.andrew.cmu.edu/user/pcorina/">Corina P&#259;s&#259;reanu</a> and <a href="https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=FmnJtIYAAAAJ&hl=en">Divya Gopinath</a>. We are working on the (very interesting!) problem of getting system-level safety guarantees for autonomous systems that use high-dimensional perception.

